serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Additional Assistance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Additional Assistance is to provide a means by which, in exceptional circumstances, financial benefit over and above ABSTUDY entitlements is available for students and Australian Apprentices who experience severe financial difficulties meeting associated education and training costs.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Additional Incidentals Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Additional Incidentals Allowance is to assist students to meet essential course costs associated with study in an approved tertiary course. The Additional Incidentals Allowance is only payable where these costs must be incurred by all students in the course. This allowance is not intended to cover the full cost of such items.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Away from Base Assistance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Away from Base Assistance is available to assist eligible students participate in the necessary academic components of an approved course where that course requires students to travel away from their home or study location for a short period of time.  Away from Base assistance covers the student's travel costs to attend the activity and the reasonable costs of accommodation and meals while away from his/her normal place of residence.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Incidentals Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Incidentals Allowance is to assist students and Australian Apprentices to meet expenses associated with commencement of study in the approved course, such as general purpose education institution fees, textbooks, equipment and stationery.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Lawful Custody Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Lawful Custody Allowance is to assist in meeting essential study and course costs for Indigenous Australian students and Australian Apprentices who are in lawful custody.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Living Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Living Allowance is paid to assist in meeting the day to day living costs of the student or Australian Apprentice.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Pensioner Education Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Pensioner Education Supplement (PES) is to provide help and so encourage certain disadvantaged Indigenous pensioner groups, such as sole parents and people with disabilities to take up study by providing a supplement to the pension to assist with ongoing expenses associated with full-time or part-time study.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Relocation Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Relocation Allowance is available where a student has to move to another town or city to take up a Masters and Doctorate Award to assist with removal costs, up to a set maximum and fares Allowance for the student, the student's partner and dependent child/ren to relocate to the study location.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY School Fees Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY School Fees Allowance (SFA) assists students and their parent(s)/guardian(s) to meet the costs of school fees levied by the approved education institution. Home schooled and distance education students also qualify for SFA even though they do not physically attend at a school, as they may have fees levied by the education institution which meet SFA requirements.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Residential Costs Option
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Residential Costs Option (RCO) allows students living in a residential college or hostel to have their fees paid directly to the accommodation provider.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY School Term Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY School Term Allowance (STA) is a payment that is paid to the applicant for students who qualify for Schooling A to assist with expenses associated with equipping the student for school, e.g. uniforms, textbooks and materials. STA is available for secondary students under 16 living at home or not eligible for the away from home, independent or pensioner rates, and primary school students aged 14 at 1 January in the year of study. Home schooled and distance education students also qualify for School Term Allowance even though they do not physically attend at an education institution.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Thesis Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Thesis Allowance is for students who are undertaking or have completed Masters or Doctorate studies to assist with costs associated with the presentation of a thesis or other similar course requirement, e.g. the costs of printing, publishing and binding the thesis. This allowance is a contribution to the costs of production of the thesis, and does not include costs such as a purchase of computer equipment.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY Under 16 Boarding Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: ABSTUDY Under 16 Boarding Supplement is to assist boarding schools that have a significant number of Indigenous enrolments with the shortfall in boarding and tuition fees paid to an eligible school for students under 16 years of age who receive a lower rate of ABSTUDY Living Allowance than those aged between 16 and 20 years. These boarding schools would then receive the same rate of assistance for all their eligible secondary school students who are entitled to Living Allowance and approved for Away from Home entitlements.

serviceDimensions.name: Age Pension
serviceDimensions.description: Age Pension (AGE) is an income support payment paid to people who: have reached qualifying pension age, and fulfil residence requirements, and are resident in Australia at the date of claim or are resident in a country which has a current International Agreement with Australia, and do not have adequate levels of income or assets that can be used to support themselves.

serviceDimensions.name: Aged Care Means Test Assessments
serviceDimensions.description: Aged Care Means Test Assessments, for both social security customers and self funded retirees, assess a care recipient's combined income and assets to determine eligibility for assistance from the Government with the cost of care.

serviceDimensions.name: Assistance for Isolated Children Scheme Additional Boarding Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: AIC Scheme Additional Boarding Allowance (ABA) is a means-tested supplementary payment to provide additional support for lower-income families whose geographically isolated student boards away from their principal family home. ABA is payable only if the actual boarding charges are greater than the minimum threshold of the rate of Basic Boarding Allowance less $250 for incidentals.

serviceDimensions.name: Assistance for Isolated Children Scheme Boarding Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: AIC Sheme Boarding Allowance (BA) is intended to contribute towards the costs incurred by families in boarding a student away from home to have daily access to appropriate schooling and who meets an isolation condition or special need.

serviceDimensions.name: Assistance for Isolated Children Scheme Distance Education Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: AIC Scheme Distance Education Allowance (DED) contributes towards incidental costs incurred by geographically isolated families whose student children are undertaking their education by distance education methods. This payment is not intended to meet the ongoing cost of provision of education (e.g. costs associated with teaching, tuition and supervision).

serviceDimensions.name: Assistance for Isolated Children Scheme Pensioner Education Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: AIC Scheme Pensioner Education Supplement (PES) is intended to contribute towards educational costs incurred by parents of geographically isolated students undertaking primary or ungraded levels of study. PES is paid for students receiving, or who qualify for, a Disability Support Pension or a Parenting Payment (Single) and qualify for either Boarding Allowance, Second Home Allowance or Distance Education allowances (as applicable), except for the requirement not to be receiving a pension.

serviceDimensions.name: Assistance for Isolated Children Scheme Second Home Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: AIC Scheme Second Home Allowance (SHA) contributes towards the costs incurred by geographically isolated families in maintaining a second family home for a student to have daily access to appropriate schooling.

serviceDimensions.name: Approved Program of Work Supplement
serviceDimensions.comment: How is this different from SVC_131?
serviceDimensions.description: Approved Program of Work Supplement (APWS) is a supplementary fortnightly payment available to assist people on eligible income support payments with the costs of participating in an approved program of work.

serviceDimensions.name: Assurance of Support Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Assurance of Support Scheme (AOS) provides a means for intending migrants who do not meet the conditions for independent admission to Australia, to enter under the assurance that an Australian resident or organisation will support them. The person who, or organisation which, elects to assure the intending migrant signs an agreement called an Assurance of Support, and is known as the assurer.

serviceDimensions.name: Austudy
serviceDimensions.description: Austudy is a payment that aims to provide income support for mature students and Australian Apprentices (apprentices or trainees), aged 25 years and older, who do not have adequate levels of income.

serviceDimensions.name: Baby Bonus
serviceDimensions.description: Baby Bonus (BB) is a payment to assist families with the extra costs of caring for a newborn or adopted child born, or entrusted to care as part of an adoption process, before 1 March 2014.

serviceDimensions.name: Bali Lifetime Rehabilitation Assistance Package
serviceDimensions.description: The Bali Lifetime Rehabilitation Assistance Package provides lifetime assistance for rehabilitation care to eligible people injured in the 2002 and 2005 Bali bombings.

serviceDimensions.name: Bereavement Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Breavement Allowance (BVA) is a short term income support payment to help customers after the death of their partner. It is generally payable for a 14 week period from the date the partner died. BVA can be claimed where either the claimant or the deceased was not receiving a social security pension or benefit at the time of death.

serviceDimensions.name: Bereavement Payment
serviceDimensions.description: A Lumpsum Bereavement Payment (LBP) is payable to certain income support customers after the death of their partner, and in some cases to a Carer Payment (CP) or Carer Allowance (CA) customer after the death of a person they were caring for.

serviceDimensions.name: Carer Adjustment Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Carer Adjustment Payment (CAP) is a payment for families where, following a More Informationcatastrophic event involving a young child aged under seven years, the family is going through a period of significant adjustment as a result of the care needs of the child. The CAP is to assist families with additional costs during their adjustment period immediately after the event.

serviceDimensions.name: Carer Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Carer Allowance (adult) is a fortnightly income supplement for people who provide additional daily care and attention for an adult with a disability or medical condition. Carer Allowance is not subject to income and asset tests, is not taxable and can be paid in addition to wages, Carer Payment or any other income support payment. To be eligible for Carer Allowance a carer must be providing additional care and attention on a daily basis, for an adult (16 years or over).

serviceDimensions.name: Carer Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Carer Payment (adult) is an income support payment that provides support to people who, because of the demands of their caring role, are unable to support themselves through substantial paid employment. Carers who personally provide constant care to a person 16 years or over with a severe disability or severe medical condition may receive Carer Payment.

serviceDimensions.name: Carer Supplement

serviceDimensions.description: Carer Supplement (CS) is an annual payment introduced in June 2009, to assist people with caring responsibilities. The eligibility date was 12 May in 2009 and 1 July from 2010 onwards. The CS replaces the One-Off Carer Bonus paid from 2004 to 2008.

serviceDimensions.name: Centrelink Compensation Recovery
serviceDimensions.description: The Centrelink Compensation Recovery program - debt recovery, recovers outstanding debts owed to the Australian Government. Debts occurs when a person has already received compensation for the injury or illness and also claims benefits from the government. It aims to prevent 'double dipping' in Income Support paid by the Commonwealth in relation to an injury or illness.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Care Benefit
serviceDimensions.description: Approved Child Care Benefit (CCF) is a payment to help families with the cost of child care. Child Care Benefit approved child care is provided by child care services approved by the Department of Education.  Most long day care, family day care, before and after school care, vacation care, in home care and occasional care services are Child Care Benefit approved child care services.  Registered Child Care Benefit (CCI) is a payment to help with the cost of child care for families using registered child care.  Registered care is child care provided by nannies, grandparents, relatives or friends who are registered with us.  In some circumstances it can also include child care provided by individuals in private pre-schools, kindergartens and some outside school hours care services.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Care Rebate
serviceDimensions.description: Child Care Rebate (CCR) is an additional payment to Child Care Benefit and covers a percentage of out-of-pocket expenses for CCB approved care.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Disability Assistance Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Child Disability Assistance Payment (CDAP) is available for carers of children with a disability and is payable in addition to the payment of Carer Allowance (CA) for the child. Families caring for a child with a disability may receive an annual payment of $1000 to help them purchase assistance for their child - for example, to purchase a wheelchair, install a hoist in the family home, modify the family car, or for respite care or therapy. The payment will be made for each child who qualifies their parent/carer for payment of CA. This money can be spent however the family chooses.

serviceDimensions.name: Commonwealth Seniors Health Card
serviceDimensions.description: Commonwealth Seniors Health Card (CSHC) is currently issued to people of age pension age who: do not qualify for the pension because of income or assets, but have income below the applicable cut offs. The CSHC provides access to pharmaceuticals under the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme at a concessional rate.

serviceDimensions.name: Crisis Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Crisis Payment (CrP) is a one-off, non-taxable payment that is designed to help new and existing Department of Human Services customers who are in severe financial hardship and identifying customers who may qualify for CrP under the released prisoner or extreme circumstances categories.

serviceDimensions.name: Dad and Partner Pay
serviceDimensions.description: Dad and Partner Pay (DAP) is an income tested and work tested payment to support eligible working fathers or partners (including adopting parents and parents in same-sex relationships) caring for a child born or who entered your care on or after 1 January 2013. Dad and Partner Pay is a taxable payment paid at the rate of the National Minimum Wage for a maximum of 2 weeks.

serviceDimensions.name: Disability Support Pension
serviceDimensions.description: Disability Support Pension (DSP) is an income support payment for people who are aged between 16 years and age pension age (when claiming), satisfy the residence criteria, and either: are permanently blind, or have a physical, intellectual or psychiatric disability causing functional incapacity of at least 20 points as measured by the Impairment Tables, and have a Continuing Inability to Work (CITW), or are participating in Supported Wage System (SWS).

serviceDimensions.name: Double Orphan Pension
serviceDimensions.description: Double Orphan Pension (DOP) is a  non-means tested payment which can be paid to a customer or an Approved Care Organisation (ACO) caring for a young person who is orphaned or unable to be cared for by their parents in certain circumstances.

serviceDimensions.name: Education Entry Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Education Entry Payment (EdEP) is payable to qualified recipients to aid in the costs associated in returning to full time study. Recipients of certain social security payments may qualify for EdEP if they are enrolled in an approved full time course of education or if a pensioner education supplement is payable.

serviceDimensions.name: Energy Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Energy Supplement (ES) provides financial assistance to pensioners and low income households.

serviceDimensions.name: Essential Medical Equipment Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Essential Medical Equipment Payment (EMEP) is an annual non-taxable payment to eligible customers covered by specific Commonwealth concession cards, who will experience additional home energy costs resulting from the use of essential medical equipment to manage their disability or medical condition.

serviceDimensions.name: Ex-Carer Allowance (child) Health Care Card
serviceDimensions.description: Ex-Carer Allowance (child) Health Care Card (EHC) is a card issued to eligible ex-Carer Allowance (CA) (child) care receivers when they turn 16. A proportion of 15 year old care receivers whose disability or medical condition attracted Carer Allowance (CA) (child) for their carer will no longer qualify for a Health Care Card (HCC) once they turn 16, despite having the same condition and facing the same pharmaceutical costs.

serviceDimensions.name: Family Tax Benefit
serviceDimensions.description: Family Tax Benefit (FTB) is a payment to help families with the cost of raising children. It consists of two parts: FTB Part A is a payment to help raise children and increases with the number of children in care; FTB Part B provides additional assistance to families with one main income earner. The rate depends on the age of the youngest child rather than the number of children.

serviceDimensions.name: Fares Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Fares Allowance (FAA) is available to: certain tertiary students receiving Youth Allowance, Austudy payment or Pensioner Education Supplement (PES) and  certain tertiary students or secondary students receiving ABSTUDY or ABSTUDY PES who live away from their permanent home while undertaking study.

serviceDimensions.name: Foster Child Health Care Card
serviceDimensions.description: The Foster Child Health Care Card (FST HCC) is issued to the foster carer but only the foster child is named on and covered by the card. It enables foster carers to purchase Pharmaceutical Benefit Scheme (PBS) medications at reduced costs for foster children and may entitle them to concessions offered by State or Territory organisations for the foster children.

serviceDimensions.name: Grandparent Child Care Benefit
serviceDimensions.description: Grandparent Child Care Benefit (GCCB) is an additional rate of CCB for approved care that recognises the highly important role that grandparents play by taking on the parenting role when parents are unable to care for children.

serviceDimensions.name: Health Care Card
serviceDimensions.description: Health Care Card (HCC) is a  card issued by Centrelink under Commonwealth Health or Social Security legislation. Its primary purpose is to indicate a customer's entitlement to Commonwealth Health concessions such as pharmaceutical benefits. The HCC is also used as proof of a person's entitlement to concessions offered by State and local government authorities. Many private companies also offer concessions to HCC holders.

serviceDimensions.name: Health Care Card (FTB)
serviceDimensions.description: Health Care Card (FTB) (HCC FTB) is a  card generally issued to customers eligible for the maximum rate of income tested FTB Part A. A customer's (HCC) includes any dependent children of the customer (and their partner if applicable) aged under 16 years of age and any dependent full-time secondary students aged 16-18 years.

serviceDimensions.name: Incentive Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Incentive Allowance (IA) is a 'saved' payment (dating back to 1989) paid to customers who are in sheltered employment. The aim of IA was to provide an incentive for customers to enter into one of these activities. IA was abolished on 12 November 1991.

serviceDimensions.name: Income Management - BasicsCard
serviceDimensions.description: Income Management / BasicsCard  works by setting aside a percentage of a customer's fortnightly entitlement to certain payments. A percentage of a customer's welfare payment is directed to meeting priority needs such as food, clothing and accommodation. The remaining percentage of a customer's payments will be paid to them in the usual way to be used at their discretion. The BasicsCard is a reusable card which allows customers to use their income managed funds to purchase goods and services at approved BasicsCard merchants through the Electronic Funds Transfer at Point of Sale (EFTPOS) network.

serviceDimensions.name: Income Management Matched Savings Scheme Payment
serviceDimensions.description: The Matched Savings Scheme Payment (MSSP) provides an incentive for people subject to a compulsory measure of Income Management (except the Cape York Initiative) to develop a savings pattern and build functional financial capability.

serviceDimensions.name: Income Support Bonus
serviceDimensions.description: The Income Support Bonus (ISB) is a non-taxable, lump sum payment paid to qualifying income support recipients in March and September each year.

serviceDimensions.name: International Social Security Agreements
serviceDimensions.description: International Social Security Agreements are international treaties made between Australia and another country, relating to social security. Agreements generally come about through the wish to coordinate the social security systems of each country to close gaps in coverage for people who work in and move between the countries. Both countries seek to share responsibility for a customer's overall retirement income and may pay a part pension based on how long the customer has lived and/or worked in each country.

serviceDimensions.name: Job Commitment Bonus
serviceDimensions.description: The Job Commitment Bonus (JCB)  provides a payment of $2500 to job seekers aged 18 to 30 who have been unemployed for 12 months or more and are receiving Newstart or Youth Allowance (Jobseeker) if they get a job and remain employed (and off Newstart or Youth Allowance (Jobseeker) for a continuous period of 12 months. Job seekers will receive a further $4,000 if they remain in a job and do not receive Newstart or Youth Allowance (Jobseeker) for a continuous period of 24 months.

serviceDimensions.name: Jobs, Education and Training Child Care Fee Assistance
serviceDimensions.description: Job, Education and Training Child Care Fee Assistance (JETCCFA) provides extra help with the cost of CCB approved care for eligible parents undertaking activities as part of an Employment Pathway Plan to help them enter or re-enter the workforce. JETCCFA covers most of the gap fee after the customer's Child Care Benefit (CCB) fee reduction is applied. JETCCFA is paid to approved child care services, including long day care, family day care, in-home care, outside school hours care, vacation care and some occasional care services.

serviceDimensions.name: Language, Literacy and Numeracy Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: The Language, Literacy and Numeracy Supplement (LLNS) may be available to customers who participate in Skills for Education and Employment (SEE).  The LLNS provides financial assistance for job seekers who want to improve their language, literacy and numeracy skills as part of their plan to return to work. This assistance is to enable job seekers undertaking SEE to meet the additional costs associated with attendance and provides an incentive for them to participate in the program.

serviceDimensions.name: Large Family Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Large Family Supplement (LFS) is paid as part of Family Tax Benefit (FTB) Part A to families with three or more FTB children.

serviceDimensions.name: Low Income Family Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Low Income Family Supplement is an administrative name for the Low Income Supplement. The name applies to customers who received or were eligible for Family Tax Benefit (FTB) for 39 weeks or more in the previous financial year. It is an annual lump sum payment available to independent adults in low income households that do not receive adequate assistance through tax cuts or other assistance payments.

serviceDimensions.name: Low Income Health Care Card
serviceDimensions.description: Low Income Health Care Card also known as a Low Income Card (LIC) a  Low Income Health Care Card entitles the customer to Commonwealth health concessions such as pharmaceutical benefits. It may also provide access to a limited range of State and Local Government concessions such as health, household, educational, recreational, and transport. Many private companies also offer concessions to Low Income Health Care Card holders.

serviceDimensions.name: Low Income Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Low Income Supplement (LIS) is an annual non-taxable lump sum payment available to independent adults in low income households that do not receive adequate assistance through tax cuts or other assistance payments.

serviceDimensions.name: Mobility Allowance
serviceDimensions.description:
Mobility Allowance (MOB) is paid to people with disabilities over the age of 16 to provide financial assistance with transport costs for those who are undertaking certain activities and are unable to use public transport without substantial assistance.
It is not essential for a customer to be in receipt of an Income Support Payment (e.g. DSP) in order to receive Mobility Allowance.

serviceDimensions.name: Multiple Birth Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Multiple Birth Allowance (MBA) is payable to customers with three or more FTB children born during the same birth up until they turn 16 years of age. For children aged 16-18 years, MBA is only payable for periods where at least three children of the birth set are full-time secondary students.

serviceDimensions.name: Newborn Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Newborn Supplement (NBS) helps families with the additional costs of caring for a newborn or adopted child. It can be paid for a child born, or entrusted to care as part of an adoption process, on or after 1 March 2014. It replaces Baby Bonus (BBY). NBS is an add-on component of a customer's Family Tax Benefit (FTB) Part A entitlement for up to 13 weeks (or 91 days).

serviceDimensions.name: Newborn Upfront Payment
serviceDimensions.description: In most circumstances where a customer is eligible for NBS for at least one day, a Newborn Upfront Payment (NBU) is payable. The NBU is a separate amount to the NBS and is not an add-on component of FTB Part A.

serviceDimensions.name: Newstart Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Newstart Allowance (NSA) is designed to ensure that people aged 22 and over who are unemployed receive an adequate level of income & participate in activities designed to increase their chances of finding work. NSA can be paid to temporarily incapacitated people who do not qualify for Sickness Allowance (SkA) because they are under the statutory age limit for SkA or because they do not have a job or study to return to.

serviceDimensions.name: Parental Leave Pay
serviceDimensions.description: Parental Leave Pay (PPL) is a taxable payment paid at the national minimum wage for a maximum of 18 weeks under the Paid Parental Leave scheme that aims to support working parents, including full-time, part-time, self-employed, casual, contract and seasonal workers who have primary care of a newborn or adopted child.

serviceDimensions.name: Parenting Payment Partnered
serviceDimensions.description: Parenting Payment Partnered (PPP) provides a taxable income support payment for a principal carer parent who is a member of a couple.

serviceDimensions.name: Parenting Payment Single
serviceDimensions.description: Parenting Payment Single (PPS) is an income support payment for single customers with principal care of a dependent child. To be paid PPS, the customer must be qualified and PPS must be payable to the customer.

serviceDimensions.name: Partner Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Partner Allowance (PA) is an income support payment for older people who  are partners of income support recipients and  face barriers to finding employment because of their lack of recent workforce experience. PA was introduced so that each partner of a couple receives a separate payment, rather than one of the couple receiving a combined payment. This ensures that each customer is treated as an individual rather than being dependent upon another person. There are no new grants for PA from the 20 September 2003.

serviceDimensions.name: Pension Bonus Bereavement Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Pension Bonus Bereavement Payment (PBBP)is a tax free lump sum that may be payable to the surviving partner of a deceased member of the Pension Bonus Scheme (PBS), who died on or after 1 January 2008 and had not lodged a successful claim for the Pension Bonus or Age Pension before they passed away.

serviceDimensions.name: Pension Bonus Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Pension Bonus Scheme (PBS) provides a tax free lump sum bonus for people who choose to work past age pension age and defer claiming an Age Pension. The Pension Bonus Scheme (PBS) is closed to new registrations from 1 July 2014.

serviceDimensions.name: Pension Bonus Top-up
serviceDimensions.description: The Pension Bonus Top-up Payment (PBTP) was implemented for all Age Pension customers granted with a commencement date on or after 1 January 2008. PBTP is a tax free payment. The PBTP is not a second bonus payment, it is a recalculation of the original bonus amount.

serviceDimensions.name: Pension Loans Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Pension Loans Scheme (PLS) allows customers of age pension age (or their partner) who receive a part pension or who cannot get a pension because either their income or assets are over the limits (but not both) access to capital tied up in their real estate assets. The PLS is a voluntary arrangement which provides support in the form of a top up of their rate of fortnightly payment via a loan, secured against Australian real estate owned by the customer.

serviceDimensions.name: Pension Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Pension Supplement (PS) replaced Utilities Allowance (UA), Telephone Allowance (TAL) at the higher rate, Pharmaceutical Allowance (PhA) and the GST Supplement for some customers from 20 September 2009.

serviceDimensions.name: Pensioner Concession Card
serviceDimensions.description: A Pensioner Concession Card (PCC) is a concession card issued by Centrelink on behalf of the Department of Social Services (DSS), under Commonwealth Health or social security legislation. Its primary purpose is to indicate a customer's entitlement to Commonwealth Health concessions such as pharmaceutical benefits.

serviceDimensions.name: Pensioner Education Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Pensioner Education Supplement (PES) is paid in addition to the primary 'qualifying' payment to help with the ongoing costs associated with study.

serviceDimensions.name: Pharmaceutical Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Pharmaceutical Allowance (PhA) is paid to assist customers financially with the purchase of prescription medicines through the Pharmaceutical Benefit Scheme (PBS).
