serviceDimensions.name: Relocation Scholarship
serviceDimensions.description: Relocation Scholarship (RS) is intended to assist students who have to live away from home to study with the cost of establishing and maintaining accommodation away from their usual home in order to undertake qualifying higher education studies.

serviceDimensions.name: Remote Area Allowance
serviceDimensions.TODO: Part of  Age Pension, Disability Support Pension, Newstart Allowance, Parenting Payment single or Youth Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Remote Area Allowance (RAA) is paid to assist customers with the higher costs of living in a remote area.

serviceDimensions.name: Rent Assistance
serviceDimensions.TODO:: Part of  Income support, FTB, DSP
serviceDimensions.description: Rent Assistance (RA) is a supplementary payment added on to the pension, allowance or benefit of income support recipients and low income families in the private rental market, in recognition of the housing costs they face.

serviceDimensions.name: Seniors Supplement
serviceDimensions.TODO: You need to be a Commonwealth Seniors Health Card holder in order to get the Seniors Supplement.
serviceDimensions.description: The Seniors Supplement (SSP) was introduced from 20 September 2009 to replace Seniors Concession Allowance (SCA) and Telephone Allowance (TAL) (including the payment for internet usage) for Commonwealth Seniors Health Card (CSHC) holders.

serviceDimensions.name: Schoolkids Bonus
serviceDimensions.description: The Schoolkids Bonus (SkB) is designed to deliver education assistance to families on an ongoing basis. These payments are paid to eligible families in January and July each year from 2013 onwards.

serviceDimensions.name: Sickness Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Sickness Allowance (SkA) aims to provide income support for people who: are temporarily incapacitated for their usual work or study and do not have adequate levels of income support. These people are able to resume their usual employment, or intend to return to their usual studies once they have recovered from their incapacity.

serviceDimensions.name: Single Income Family Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Single Income Family Supplement (SIFS) is an annual non-taxable payment of up to $300 for families with one main income earner and single parent families who, unlike dual income families with similar household incomes, receive little or no assistance through tax changes under the Household Assistance Package.

serviceDimensions.name: Special Benefit
serviceDimensions.description: Special Benefit (SpB) aims to provide income support for people who, due to reasons beyond their control, are: in financial hardship; unable to earn a sufficient livelihood for themselves and their dependents.

serviceDimensions.name: Special Child Care Benefit
serviceDimensions.description: Special Child Care Benefit (SCCB) can pay up to the full cost of approved child care fees where the child is at risk of serious abuse or neglect or the family is experiencing a hardship that substantially reduces the capacity to pay child care fees. SCCB is additional assistance above the normal CCB available to families using child care provided by an Approved Service Provider (ASP).

serviceDimensions.name: Special Disability Trusts
serviceDimensions.description: A Special Disability Trust (SDT) is a private trust established for a sole beneficiary, who has a severe disability or medical condition, by the parent/s or a close relative for the future care and accommodation needs of the beneficiary.

serviceDimensions.name: Stillborn Baby Payment
serviceDimensions.TODO: Need to link this to having a baby life event, but concerned about making sure it might not be seen as a offensive assosiation
serviceDimensions.description: Stillborn Baby Payment (SBP) is a payment for a stillborn baby delivered on or after 1 March 2014. The payment is available as a lump sum payment to eligible customers. It replaces Baby Bonus (BBY) as a payment to support customers after a stillbirth.

serviceDimensions.name: Student Start-up Scholarship
serviceDimensions.description: Student Start-up Scholarship (SSS) is intended to assist students with the up-front costs of tertiary study such as textbooks and specialised equipment.

serviceDimensions.name: Telephone Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Telephone Allowance (TAL) is a payment made quarterly to eligible telephone subscribers with their first income support payment issued on or after the following dates of each year: 1 January; 20 March; 1 July; and 20 September.

serviceDimensions.name: Transition to Independent Living Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Transition to Independent Living Allowance (TILA) is assistance which is provided to, or on behalf of young people leaving formal care, to assist them to make the transition to independent living.

serviceDimensions.name: Utilities Allowance
serviceDimensions.TODO: Disability Support Pension Partner Allowance or Widow Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Utilities Allowance (UA) is paid to certain customers to assist in meeting the cost of regular bills such as gas, electricity and water.

serviceDimensions.name: Voluntary Incentive Payment
serviceDimensions.description: The Voluntary Income Management Incentive Payment is a non-taxable payment, which is paid automatically for every 26 weeks of continuous Voluntary Income Management.

serviceDimensions.name: Widow Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Widow Allowance (WA) was introduced to provide an income support option for older women who had lost the support of a partner (through death, divorce or separation) and who had no recent workforce experience. WA will be phased out from 1 July 2005 with new grants from this date only to be made to women who were born on or before 1 July 1955.

serviceDimensions.name: Widow B Pension
serviceDimensions.description: Widow B Pension (WidB) is an income support payment available to certain older widows who did not qualify for Parenting Payment (PP), have limited means of support, and lost the financial support of their partner. There have been no new grants of WidB since 20 March 1997.

serviceDimensions.name: Wife Pension
serviceDimensions.description: Wife Pension (WP) is a payment that was abolished on 1 July 1995. It was originally intended to provide income support to the female partners of male Disability Support Pension (DSP) and male Age Pension customers in recognition of their possibly limited workforce experience.

serviceDimensions.name: Youth Allowance Apprentice
serviceDimensions.description: Youth Allowance Apprentice is an income support payment for Australian Apprentices (apprentices or trainees) aged 16 - 24 undertaking or intending to undertake an approved course of study which aims to: ensure eligible young people receive adequate levels of income while studying or training; encourage young people to choose further education or training over job search if they do not have sufficient skills to obtain long-term employment; and encourage young people to undertake a range of activities that will promote entry into employment. Some 15 year olds may qualify for Youth Allowance (YA) and some full-time students and Australian Apprentices continue to qualify for YA after they turn 25. Assistance for students or Australian Apprentices aged 25 years or over is generally provided under Austudy.

serviceDimensions.name: Youth Allowance Jobseeker
serviceDimensions.description: Youth Allowance Jobseeker (YNST) is an income support payment for young Australians generally aged 16 - 21 which aims to: ensure eligible young people receive adequate levels of income while studying, training, looking for, or preparing for, paid employment, encourage young people to choose further education or training over job search if they do not have sufficient skills to obtain long-term employment, and encourage young people to undertake a range of activities that will promote entry into employment. YNST may also be paid to customers who are: under 22 years, and temporarily unable to work due to an illness or injury or have claimed Disability Support Pension (DSP) and are awaiting the assessment of the claim or are under 16 years of age and independent.

serviceDimensions.name: Youth Allowance Student
serviceDimensions.description: Youth Allowance Student (YFST) is an income support payment for students aged 16 - 24 undertaking or intending to undertake an approved course of study which aims to: ensure eligible young people receive adequate levels of income while studying or training; encourage young people to choose further education or training over job search if they do not have sufficient skills to obtain long-term employment; and encourage young people to undertake a range of activities that will promote entry into employment. Some 15 year olds may qualify for Youth Allowance (YA) and some full-time students and Australian Apprentices continue to qualify for YA after they turn 25. Assistance for students or Australian Apprentices aged 25 years or over is generally provided under Austudy.

serviceDimensions.name: Youth Disability Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: Youth Disability Supplement (YDS) is available to recipients of Disability Support Pension who are 21 years of age or under or Youth Allowance and ABSTUDY recipients who are 21 years of age and under and have been assessed by an Employment Services Assessment (ESAt) or Job Capacity Assessment (JCA) as having a partial capacity to work of less than 30 hours per week.

serviceDimensions.name: Australian Government Disaster Recovery Payment
serviceDimensions.description: The AGDRP is to provide immediate, short term financial assistance to eligible Australian residents who are adversely affected by a designated natural or non-natural disaster, whether within Australia or offshore.

serviceDimensions.name: Australian Victim of Terrorism Overseas Payment
serviceDimensions.description: The Australian Victim of Terrorism Overseas Payment (AVTOP) is a one-off payment that provides assistance to a: primary victim  - a person who was  harmed as a direct result  of a declared overseas terrorist act, and/or; secondary victim - a person who is the  close family member of a deceased person , who died as a  direct result of a declared overseas terrorist act. The AVTOP is non-taxable and is not to be treated as compensation.

serviceDimensions.name: Disaster Recovery Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Disaster Recovery Allowance (DRA) will provide short term income support to eligible individuals (employees, primary producers and sole traders) who have suffered a loss of income as a direct result of a major or widespread disaster as declared by the Attorney General for the purposes of the Social Security Act 1991.

serviceDimensions.name: Ex Gratia - Assistance for New Zealanders
serviceDimensions.description: Ex Gratia Assistance for New Zealanders is assistance for New Zealand non-protected special category visa holders (sub-class 444). The Ex Gratia Assistance for New Zealanders is a one off payment for people who have been adversely affected by a disaster.

serviceDimensions.name: Ex Gratia - Income Support Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Ex Gratia - Income Support Allowance may be activated in the case of a disaster situation. A customer may only receive a DRA or Ex Gratia - Income Support Allowance for the same event, not both. The policy covering these payments is owned and developed by the Attorney-General's Department. Because every emergency is different and the impact on individuals can vary, Ex Gratia - Income Support Allowance policy is tailored to meet those needs.

serviceDimensions.name: Centrelink Confirmation eServices
serviceDimensions.description: Centrelink Confirmation eServices (CCeS) Contracts is an electronic (online) system designed to provide an approved organisation with verification and confirmation of a customer's details and concession entitlement. The amount of information that can be provided to an approved concession provider is negotiated with the Department of Human Services.

serviceDimensions.name: Centrelink Information Exchange Service
serviceDimensions.description: The Centrelink Information Exchange Service helps businesses securely exchange documents and electronic files with DHS.

serviceDimensions.name: Centrelink Payment Summary
serviceDimensions.description: Centrelink Payment Summaries (previously known as Group Certificates) are available on request for customers to access who were in receipt of a taxable payment and/or tax related components irrespective of whether tax has been deducted from the payments. Payment Summaries are also generated for customers who were previously on payments.

serviceDimensions.name: Centrepay
serviceDimensions.description: Centrepay is a free and voluntary bill paying service available for customers to pay their bills directly from their Centrelink payments. Customers receiving an eligible Centrelink administered payment can nominate to have amounts deducted from their payment for bills such as private rent, gas, electricity, water, council rates, ambulance services, telephone, education fees, funeral benefit schemes, legal fees, whitegoods and medical expenses. Deductions are transferred directly to a Centrepay Third Party Organisation (TPO) for part or full payment for services.

serviceDimensions.name: Financial Information Service
serviceDimensions.description: The Financial Information Service (FIS) is a free education and expert information service provided by the Government. FIS helps people to make informed decisions about investment and financial issues by assisting them to understand their own financial affairs and the options available to them. FIS provides a service by phone, appointment and through seminars.

serviceDimensions.name: Grandparent Advisers
serviceDimensions.description: Grandparent Advisers provide support for grandparents with full time caring responsibility for their grandchildren. Advisers can help by: understanding family circumstances to provide tailored information about payments and services; arranging appointments with our specialist staff, such as social workers; arranging referrals to other federal, state and community service providers.

serviceDimensions.name: Indigenous Specialist Officers
serviceDimensions.description: Indigenous Specialist Officers (ISOs) provide support to Customer Service Officers (CSOs) and local communities to improve customer service for Indigenous customers. Generally located at service centres, Indigenous Specialist Officer (ISO) duties involve: connecting Indigenous customers and community groups to the Department of Human Services (DHS) payments, services and programs and assisting them to access mainstream channels where appropriate; promoting DHS services to the local Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities, including attending community forums to educate, build awareness and increase their understanding of entitlements and obligations; providing support and formal and/or informal training to staff to improve their cultural capability and referral knowledge to improve service delivery to Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians.

serviceDimensions.name: Interpreter and Translation Services
serviceDimensions.description: Interpreter and Translation Services are provided free to help customers do business with us.

serviceDimensions.name: Multicultural Service Officers
serviceDimensions.description: Multicultural Service Officers (MSOs) are specialist staff whose role is to facilitate government programs aimed specifically at customers from culturally and linguistically diverse (CALD) backgrounds. Their primary focus is on enhancing access and participation in products and services delivered by the Department of Human Services. MSO positions are located in selected service centres throughout Australia. MSOs are usually the central point of contact between government and non-government organisations representing customers from CALD backgrounds. They conduct outreach and liaise with ethnic community agencies to inform customers from CALD backgrounds of the department's programs, payments and services.

serviceDimensions.name: Refugee Services
serviceDimensions.description: Refugee Services provide assistance to those who have recently arrived as a refugee, humanitarian entrant or have been granted a Permanent Protection Visa to live in Australia.

serviceDimensions.name: Rent Deduction Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Rent Deduction Scheme (RDS) provides for DHS Customers living in government housing to have their rent, loan repayments, arrears and other housing payments deducted from their Centrelink payment each fortnight and sent directly to the relevant State or Territory Housing Authority.

serviceDimensions.name: Social Work Services
serviceDimensions.description: Social Work Services incorporate the concept of socially inclusive practice with the objective of assisting the customer, regardless of experiences and circumstances, to achieve their potential.  Social workers work with customers to assist with and improve their engagement in social and economic participation.

serviceDimensions.name: Drought Co-ordinators
serviceDimensions.description: Drought Co-ordinators assist with the delivery of mental health and social support services in drought-affected areas. A network of Drought Coordinators commenced on 1 April 2014. Drought Coordinators are located in Mt Isa, Longreach, Charleville, Tamworth and Armidale to ensure coordination with state-based and local services and complement other social support efforts in their regions. Drought Coordinators will travel to drought-affected areas to facilitate social services and attend community events. The Drought Coordinators are in addition to the social and mental support services operating in drought-affected areas of New South Wales and Queensland.

serviceDimensions.name: Farm Household Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Farm Household Allowance (FHA) is an income support payment available to eligible farmers and their partners who are in financial hardship. It can be used to address all causes of hardship and is not dependent on climatic triggers or associated with drought declarations. FHA is a taxable payment that is paid at the Newstart Allowance (NSA) or Youth Allowance (YA) rate. It can be paid for a cumulative period of three years. FHA customers have access to the same benefits and services as other income support recipients and may be eligible for add-ons, depending on their circumstances.

serviceDimensions.TODO: Check incedental assignment, appears to be only for helping with FHA
serviceDimensions.name: Farm Household Case Officers
serviceDimensions.description: The role of Farm Household Case Officers: explaining the requirements for a Financial Improvement Agreement (FIA) * using the FHA recipient's Farm Financial Assessment (FFA), to inform the discussion with the recipient, to develop their FIA * contacting the FHA recipient approximately every three months to discuss the agreed activities of the FIA, including issues impacting participation in these activities * holding at least one face-to-face meeting with each FHA recipient within the three years that the recipient is receiving FHA. This meeting can be held at the recipient's farm enterprise * discussing, where appropriate, other DHS programs and services and external referrals that may be of benefit to the FHA recipient  this may include referral to services such as the RFCS.

serviceDimensions.name: Farm Financial Assessment Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: The Farm Financial Assessment Supplement is to assist in covering the cost of a prescribed adviser completing a comprehensive assessment of the financial position of a farm enterprise and the person for whom the assessment is conducted. It has multiple parts, some of which are completed by the person and some by the person's prescribed adviser.

serviceDimensions.name: Activity Supplement
serviceDimensions.TODO: This appears to be the same as the FFA supplement
serviceDimensions.description: The Activity Supplement is for the purpose of funding, wholly, or partially, the cost of an activity specified in the FIA (up to a maximum amount). An individual can receive the activity supplement in more than one instalment (up to the maximum amount) and elect to receive the activity supplement directly or have it paid to a provider.

serviceDimensions.name: Assessment Subsidy for Overseas Trained Professionals Programme
serviceDimensions.description: Assessment Subsidy for Overseas Trained Professionals Programme (ASDOT) is to enable eligible overseas trained Australian residents to obtain recognition of their qualifications for the purposes of registration and/or employment in Australia. The programme provides grants for approved assessments and/or examinations that are necessary to qualify for employment in Australia, by professions that are self-regulated by law.

serviceDimensions.name: Status Resolution Support Services Payment
serviceDimensions.description: Status Resolution Support Services (SRSS) payment is a  support payment for eligible recipients who are awaiting resolution of their immigration status. The payment comprises a Living Allowance, Rental Assistance Allowance and Dependent Child Allowance. The SRSS payment is paid under the Financial Management and Accountability Act 1997 rather than social security law.

serviceDimensions.name: Half Fare Transport Concession Card
serviceDimensions.description: Half Fare Transport Concession Cards are available to NSW residents receiving unemployment or other eligible Commonwealth benefits at the maximum rate and looking for a job entitling them to a half-fare single and return travel on some buses, trains, light rail and ferry services.

serviceDimensions.name: Helping Young Parents
serviceDimensions.description: The Helping Young Parents Programme (HYP) aims to assist and support young parents in overcoming barriers so they can complete their education to a Year 12 or equivalent qualification (Certificate II). The programme also encourages young parents to access services and opportunities available locally to assist in achieving education and training outcomes for themselves, and health and education outcomes for their children.  This initiative will support and engage a vulnerable group within the Australian population by linking them to the current service system and provide support that is tailored to the level of an individual's need.

serviceDimensions.name: JobSearch Facilities
serviceDimensions.description: JobSearch Facilities, include printers and self-service computers located in the public areas of DHS. These facilities are free of charge and can help customers identify employment opportunities as well as assist in making contact with Employment Service Providers. These providers may be able to help you in their search for work.

serviceDimensions.name: Supporting Jobless Families
serviceDimensions.description: The Supporting Jobless Families Programme (SJF) aims to support the long-term participation and productivity of parents who are out of work. The programme will support eligible customers in achieving: Better health and early development outcomes for their children by promoting the services and support available locally; Enhanced school readiness and school transitions for pre-school aged children by promoting the benefits of early childhood learning and education such as preschool; Looking for work by informing and supporting parents to increase their capacity to overcome prevocational barriers to employment and be more engaged in the community.

serviceDimensions.name: Community Development Employment Projects Participant Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: The Community Development Employment Project Participant Supplement (CPS) is an additional payment made to eligible CDEP wages participants. Community Development Employment Projects (CDEP) wages participants receive CDEP wages for their participation in the Remote Jobs and Communities Programme (RJCP).

serviceDimensions.name: Australian Childhood Immunisation Register
serviceDimensions.description: The Australian Childhood Immunisation Register (ACIR) is a national register that records vaccination details for children under seven years of age who live in Australia.

serviceDimensions.name: Australian Organ Donor Register
serviceDimensions.description: The Australian Organ Donor Register (AODR) is a national register that records an individuals legal decision about donating organs and / or tissues for transplantion.

serviceDimensions.name: Better Access Initiative (Mental Health Care)
serviceDimensions.description: The Better Access Initiative (Mental Health Care) is the government's commitment to provide better access to mental health care for patients with mental disorders includes Medicare Benefits Schedule items for consultant psychiatrists, general practitioners (GPs), psychologists, clinical psychologists, occupational therapists, social workers. Chronic Disease Management items continue to be available for patients with chronic medical conditions.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Dental Benefits Schedule
serviceDimensions.description:
The Child Dental Benefits Schedule (CDBS) provides financial support for basic dental services for children aged 2-17.  It provides eligible children with a capped benefit of $1000 (indexed annually) over two calendar years for basic dental services. The eligibility of a child is determined by meeting an age requirement, a means test, and they must also be eligible for Medicare services.
The CDBS replaces the Medicare Teen Dental Plan from 1 January 2014.

serviceDimensions.name: Cleft Lip and Cleft Palate Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Cleft Lip and Cleft Palate Scheme helps with treatment costs for specialised services for cleft lip and cleft palate conditions. The Scheme provides Medicare benefits for a range of dental treatment provided by certain eligible practitioners, including: some orthodontic work; simple and surgical extraction of teeth; some general and prosthodontic services by your family dentist; oral and maxillofacial surgery.

serviceDimensions.name: Competitive Advantage Payment
serviceDimensions.description: The Medical Indemnity (Competitive Advantage Payment) Bill 2005, provides that medical indemnity insurance groups that benefited from the Incurred But Not Reported (IBNR) indemnity scheme will make a series of payments to the Government to address the competitive advantage arising from that support. In addition, doctors who had a liability under the United Medical Protection Support Payment arrangements will now pay less.

serviceDimensions.name: External Breast Prostheses Reimbursement Programme
serviceDimensions.description: The External Breast Prostheses Reimbursement Programme provides reimbursements for external breast prostheses for women who have had a mastectomy as a result of breast cancer.

serviceDimensions.name: General Practice Rural Incentive Programme
serviceDimensions.description: The General Practice Rural Incentive Programme aims to encourage medical practitioners to relocate to and practice in rural and remote communities and to promote careers in rural medicine. It combines two previously separate retention incentive programs available to general practitioners (GPs) and Registrars, and provides a new relocation grant.

serviceDimensions.name: Hearing Services Programme
serviceDimensions.description: The Hearing Services Program administered by the Office of Hearing Services (the Office) at the Department of Health (Health) provides hearing services and products to eligible people. The Department of Human Services administers the claim payment system for the program and provides payments for services and products to accredited hearing service providers.

serviceDimensions.name: Herceptin 'Late Stage' Breast Cancer Treatment
serviceDimensions.description: The Herceptin 'Late Stage' Breast Cancer Treatment Programme makes sure trastuzumab (Herceptin) is available free of charge for late stage metastatic breast cancer. This program is not part of the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS).  Herceptin must only be ordered by prescribers for eligible patients. All orders of Herceptin must be approved by Human Services before supply and no retrospective supplies of Herceptin will be approved by Human Services.

serviceDimensions.name: High Risk Medical Implantable Devices
serviceDimensions.description: The High Risk Medical Implantable Devices Register is a national patient contact register for implantable devices to ensure that patients with a high risk implantable device are contactable in the event of a serious safety risk associated with their device. This involved establishing nationally consistent data requirements, unique device identifiers and standard labelling for implantable devices, and a national protocol for rapid patient identification and notification.

serviceDimensions.name: Higher Education Contribution Scheme Reimbursement Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The HECS Reimbursement Scheme encourages medical graduates to pursue a career in rural medicine and increase the number of doctors in rural and regional areas. Under the Scheme, eligible medical graduates who complete their medical degree in 2000 or later, have one fifth of their HECS debt reimbursed for each year of training undertaken or service provided in Rural, Remote and Metropolitan Area (RRMA) 3-7 locations.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - Exceptional Claims Indemnity Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Exceptional Claims Indemnity Scheme (ECS) assists medical defence organisations and medical indemnity insurers where settlement amounts of claims exceed a practitioner's indemnity insurance contract limit.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - High Cost Claims Indemnity Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The High Cost Claims Indemnity Scheme (HCCS) enables the government to fund 50% of the cost of payouts by medical defence organisations and medical indemnity insurers that are greater than the applicable threshold amount, up to the limit of a practitionerï¿½s indemnity cover.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - Incurred-But-Not-Reported Indemnity Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Incurred-But-Not-Reported Indemnity Claims Scheme (IBNR) is designed to fund the IBNR liabilities of medical defence organisations where they do not have adequate reserves to cover their liabilities. Under the Act, medical defence organisations that existed on 30 June 2002 may participate in the IBNR scheme unless the Minister determines otherwise. To date, the Minister has determined that United Medical Protection Limited is the only medical defence organisation to actively participate in the IBNR indemnity scheme.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - Medical Indemnity Administration Payments
serviceDimensions.description: Medical Indemnity Administration Payments are paid to midwife professional indemnity insurers to compensate for the work they undertake to administer the scheme.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - Premium Support Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Premium Support Scheme (PSS) is an Australian Government scheme that helps eligible doctors with the costs of their medical indemnity insurance (MII). Eligible doctors see the benefit of the PSS through reductions in the level of premiums charged to them by their MII. The Australian Government makes payments to MIIs for the PSS.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - Run-Off Cover Indemnity Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Run-Off Cover Indemnity Scheme (ROCS) assists medical defence organisations and medical indemnity insurers to cover claims made against medical practitioners who have retired, have a permanent disability, are on maternity leave, or who have permanently left private medical practice in Australia.

serviceDimensions.name: Indemnity - Run-Off Cover Scheme Support Payment
serviceDimensions.TODO: Look at the midwife indemnity stuff http://www.humanservices.gov.au/health-professionals/services/midwife-professional-indemnity-scheme/
serviceDimensions.description: The Run-Off Cover Indemnity Scheme (ROCS) is funded on an ongoing basis through a charge on insurers called the Run-Off Cover Scheme Support Payment which is levied as a percentage of insurersï¿½ medical indemnity insurance income and is shown on doctorsï¿½ premium notices. The ROCS therefore ensures that eligible doctors receive medical indemnity cover that is secure, does not require further payment and is based on the cover they had while they were working.

serviceDimensions.name: Indigenous Access Programme
serviceDimensions.description: The Indigenous Access Program improves the health of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians through better access to Medicare services.  Aboriginal or a Torres Strait Islander can get better access to Medicare services to help with their health. Medicare services include the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme, the Australian Organ Donor Register, the Australian Childhood Immunisation Register and other services.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Allied Health Initiative
serviceDimensions.TODO: Seems to be part of varoiius other stuff
serviceDimensions.description: The Medicare Allied Health Initiative allows chronically ill people who are being managed by their general practitioner (GP) under a Chronic Disease Management (CDM) plan access Medicare rebates for allied health services.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Benefit Tax Statement
serviceDimensions.TODO: How does this fit into the landscape????, its a tax service but medicare does provide something here to help?
serviceDimensions.description: A Medicare Benefit Tax Statement is a listing of medical charges and Medicare benefits paid to those listed on a nominated Medicare card in a particular financial year. A Medicare benefit tax statement may help a person when claiming the net medical tax offset.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Benefits Schedule
serviceDimensions.description: The Medicare Benefits Schedule (MBS) is a Department of Health publication that lists services that are subsidised by the Australian Government under Medicare. You can use MBS Online to check if a service is listed under Medicare.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Bulk Billing
serviceDimensions.description: Medicare Bulk Billing is when a provider bills Medicare directly for any medical or allied health service that a patient receives. Bulk billing is available to all persons in Australia who are eligible for a Medicare benefit under the Medicare program.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Card
serviceDimensions.description: Medicare Cards are issued to all people who are eligible under the Health Insurance Act 1973 to claim Medicare benefits and used for visiting a doctor who bulk bills, seeking treatment as a public patient in a public hospital or having a Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme prescription filled.
serviceDimensions.TODO: This is an interesting one, it is really only a means for accessing a service???

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Compensation Recovery
serviceDimensions.description: The Medicare Compensation Recovery program - debt recovery, recovers outstanding debts owed to the Australian Government. Debts occurs when a person has already received compensation for the injury or illness and also claims benefits from the government.  It aims to prevent 'double dipping' in Medicare, Nursing Home benefits and Residential Care subsidies paid by the Commonwealth in relation to an injury or illness.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Entitlement Statement
serviceDimensions.description: The Medicare Levy Exemption is an exemption from paying the Medicare levy for people in any of the following three exemption categories at any time in the year: Category 1 - medical, which applies to people such as blind pensioners; Category 2 - foreign residents and residents of Norfolk Island; Category 3 - people not entitled to Medicare benefits and who have obtained a Medicare levy exemption certificate from Medicare Australia.

serviceDimensions.name: Medicare Safety Net
serviceDimensions.description: The Medicare Safety Net (MSN) is designed to provide financial assistance to people with high out-of-hospital medical expenses that attract a Medicare benefit. The Safety Net applies to individuals or members of registered families and is calculated on a calendar year basis provided receipts are produced.

serviceDimensions.name: Mental Health Nurse Incentive Programme
serviceDimensions.description: The Mental Health Nurse Incentive Program (MHNIP) funds community based general practices, private psychiatric practices and other appropriate organisations to engage mental health nurses to assist in the provision of coordinated clinical care for people with severe mental health disorders.

serviceDimensions.name: Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme - Level 1 Commonwealth Contributions (Claims Schemes)
serviceDimensions.description: The Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme (MPIS) includes a Commonwealth contribution initiative designed to assist with claims made against eligible midwives and encourage the provision of indemnity insurance policies for private independent midwives. For each Level 1 claim, the Insurer will pay the first $100 000. For each claim over $100 000 the Australian Government, via the Insurer, will pay 80% of the cost that exceeds the threshold, up to a ceiling of $2 million.

serviceDimensions.name: Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme - Level 2 Commonwealth Contributions (Claims Schemes)
serviceDimensions.description: The Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme (MPIS) includes a Commonwealth contribution initiative designed to assist with claims made against eligible midwives and encourage the provision of indemnity insurance policies for private independent midwives. For each Level 2 claim, the Insurer will pay the first $100 000. For each claim that exceeds $2 million, the Australian Government, via the Insurer, will pay at the Level 1 rate for the first $2 million, plus 100% of the cost of the claim above the threshold.

serviceDimensions.name: Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme - Run-Off Cover Commonwealth Contributions (Claims Scheme)
serviceDimensions.description: The Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme - Run-Off Cover Commonwealth Contributions (Claims Scheme) (ROC) is designed to assist an eligible Insurer in respect of claims made against midwives who are retired; were not engaged in private practice during the preceding 3 years; have a permanent disability; are deceased; are on maternity leave, or have permanently left private midwifery practice in Australia. ROC Commonwealth contributions reimburse the Insurer 100% of an eligible claim. Under the ROC scheme eligible claims will be paid by the Australian Government.  A levy placed on total premium costs is payable by the Insurer annually.  Levies collected will fund midwife Run-off Cover claims.

serviceDimensions.name: National Bowel Cancer Screening Register
serviceDimensions.description: The National Bowel Cancer Screening Program aims to detect cancer early and reduce cancer-related deaths. The National Bowel Cancer Screening Register is an important part of the program. The register issues invitation kits, reminder letters and keeps a record of results.

serviceDimensions.name: National Health Funding Administration Payment System
serviceDimensions.description: The National Health Funding Administrator Payments System, supports the reforms to Australian Government and state and territory government funding arrangements for hospital services. The department provides program, corporate and support services to assist the Administrator of the National Health Funding Pool and the National Health Funding Body to carry out their functions.

serviceDimensions.name: Personally Controlled Electronic Health Record
serviceDimensions.description: The Personally Controlled Electronic Health Record (PCEHR) is a secure electronic summary of a consumer's health information. A consumer can: access their eHealth record from anywhere via a website; add their own notes to their eHealth record; allow healthcare professionals to view their eHealth record information and add new information to their record. DHS manages consumer and provider contact information for the Personally Controlled Electronic Health Record (eHealth record) system.  It also provides contact centre capabilities and supporting infrastructures for registrations, enquiries, complaints and advice via phone, face-to-face, mail and online channels.

serviceDimensions.name: Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS) gives all Australian residents and eligible overseas visitors access to prescription medicine at a subsidised cost.

serviceDimensions.name: Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme Safety Net
serviceDimensions.TODO: Is this a service for DHS or TAX???
serviceDimensions.description:
The Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme Safety Net reduces the cost of prescription medicines for individuals and families once the PBS Safety Net threshold has been reached.  Each year the Commonwealth (the Department of Health) sets a Safety Net threshold amount, one each for: 
concession card holders (referred to as concession), people who don't hold a concession card (referred to as general).

serviceDimensions.name: Practice Incentives Programme Payments
serviceDimensions.description: The Practice Incentives Program (PIP) provides a number of incentives that aim to recognise general practices that provide comprehensive, quality care, and which are either accredited or working towards accreditation against the Royal Australian College of General Practitioners' (RACGP) Standards for General Practices.

serviceDimensions.name: Practice Nurse Incentive Programme
serviceDimensions.description: Practice Nurse Incentive Program (PNIP) provides incentive payments to practices to support an expanded and enhanced role for nurses working in general practice.

serviceDimensions.name: Private Health Insurance Rebate
serviceDimensions.description: The Private Health Insurance Rebate reduces the amount you pay for private health insurance.  Families and individuals that pay private health insurance premiums, and are entitled for Medicare, are eligible for the Rebate.
serviceDimensions.TODO: Users access this through private health or ATO

serviceDimensions.name: Reciprocal Health Care Agreements
serviceDimensions.description: A Reciprocal Health Care Agreement (RHCA) is an agreement between the Australian Government and certain countries. These agreements entitle residents to medically necessary health cover while visiting Australia.

serviceDimensions.name: Rural Locum Education Assistance Programme
serviceDimensions.description:
The Rural Locum Education Assistance Program (Rural LEAP) provides financial assistance to eligible urban general practitioners (GPs) who complete emergency medicine training and commit to a total of four weeks (20 working days) general practice locum placement in a rural or remote area within a two year period. This is a one off incentive which gives participants financial assistance up to a total of $6,000 to undertake emergency medicine training.
The department maintains a register of eligible GPs and makes payments to GPs when theyï¿½ve completed their first 10 working days of the locum commitment. Human Services also tracks the two year period for participants to undertake their locum commitment.

serviceDimensions.name: Rural Procedural Grant Programme
serviceDimensions.description:
The Rural Procedural Grants Program (RPGP) supports GPs who provide procedural or emergency medicine services in rural and remote areas to attend relevant training, focusing on skills maintenance and up-skilling.  Grant payments are designed to help with the cost of attending training, including course costs, locum relief and travel expenses. Grants are calculated on the number of days of training.
The department maintains a register of eligible GPs and makes payments to GPs on advice from the ACRRM and RACGP.

serviceDimensions.name: Special Assistance Schemes
serviceDimensions.description: Special Assistance Schemes provide assistance for eligible Australian residents and others who were directly or indirectly affected by acts of terrorism or natural disasters. The assistance is for health related out-of-pocket costs. These are costs not covered by Medicare, other government programs, private travel or health insurance.

serviceDimensions.name: Supporting Leave for Living Organ Donor
serviceDimensions.description: The Supporting Leave for Living Organ Donor initiative supports paid leave for living organ donors by providing a payment of up to six weeks.  The payment is available to employers whose employees have had time off work either to donate an organ (being either a kidney or partial liver) or to attend medical appointments to assess their suitability to become a living organ donor.

serviceDimensions.name: Aged Care
serviceDimensions.description: The Aged Care Assessment Program (ACAP) is a cooperative working arrangement between the Commonwealth and state and territory governments to operate Aged Care Assessment Teams (ACATs) across Australia.  The core objective of the ACAP is to comprehensively assess the care needs of frail older people and to assist them to gain access to the most appropriate types of care, including approval for Commonwealth Government subsidised care services. A person may be approved to receive one or more of the following types of care: Residential Care (including residential respite care); Home Care, and/or flexible care (Transition Care).

serviceDimensions.name: Aged Care Provider Supplement
serviceDimensions.description: An Aged Care Provider Supplement is paid to aged care facilities on behalf of residents. Aged care providers must agree to receive the supplement, if they do not agree, the resident will have to pay the increase in the maximum basic daily fee.

serviceDimensions.name: Continence Aids Payment Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Continence Aids Payment Scheme (CAPS) is a payment that will assist eligible people who have permanent and severe incontinence to meet some of the costs of their continence products.

serviceDimensions.name: Bass Strait Passenger Vehicle Equalisation Scheme
serviceDimensions.TODO: Check if this gets tagged with health
serviceDimensions.description: The Bass Strait Passenger Vehicle Equalisation Scheme (BSPVES) provides a rebate against the fare charged by a ferry operator, for an accompanied passenger vehicle or caravan. Ferry operators claim reimbursement of the BSPVES rebate from the Department of Human Services on a monthly basis.

serviceDimensions.name: Tasmanian Freight Equalisation Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Tasmanian Freight Equalisation Scheme (TFES) provides assistance to shippers of eligible goods that are transported by sea between Tasmania and the Australian mainland. Claims for TFES assistance are made directly to the Department of Human Services by the shipper, after payment of the freight costs.

serviceDimensions.name: Healthcare Identifiers Service
serviceDimensions.description: The Healthcare Identifiers Service (HI Service) is a national system for uniquely identifying healthcare providers (healthcare provider organisations and individual healthcare providers) and individuals. The department manages the allocation, maintenance and disclosure of healthcare identifiers to healthcare providers and the public.

serviceDimensions.name: National Authentication Service for Health
serviceDimensions.description:
The National Authentication Service for Health (NASH) provides Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) Certificates that help individuals or organisations to: 
 * Access the Personally Controlled Electronic Health Record (eHealth record) system. * Send and receive messages securely using software that meets the requirements of Secure Message Delivery.

serviceDimensions.name: Small Business Superannuation Clearing House
serviceDimensions.TODO: Check if this one is presented as being from DHS or tax. link on website goes to tax.
serviceDimensions.description: The Small Business Superannuation Clearing House (SBSCH) is a free online superannuation payments service that helps small businesses with 19 or fewer employees meet their superannuation guarantee obligations.

serviceDimensions.name: Payments to Health and Hospital Providers Who Treat Veterans
serviceDimensions.description: Payments to Health and Hospital Providers Who Treat Veterans are payments to medical, hospital and allied health providers who treat eligible veterans, their spouses and dependants. DHS assesses claims and make payments.

serviceDimensions.name: Provision of Concession Cards for Veterans
serviceDimensions.description: In collaboration with the Department of Veterans Affairs (DVA), the department produces DVA gold cards (for all conditions), white cards (for specific conditions) and orange cards (for pharmaceuticals).

serviceDimensions.name: Repatriation Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: The Repatriation Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (RPBS) provides a wide range of pharmaceuticals and dressings at a concessional rate for the treatment of eligible veterans, war widows/widowers, and their dependants.

serviceDimensions.name: Visiting Medical Practitioners Programme
serviceDimensions.description: Visiting Medical Practitioner Processing (VMP) is an exclusive WA program that enables specialist medical practitioners to be paid for treating public patients in public hospitals, via a real time intranet processing system.

serviceDimensions.name: Early Release of Superannuation - Compassionate Grounds
serviceDimensions.description: The Early Release of Superannuation Benefits (ERSB) programme administers the very limited circumstances where benefits may be released on specified compassionate grounds. These are: medical/dental treatment for the person or a dependant; medical/dental transport for the person or a dependant; to prevent a person's home from being sold by the mortgagee (lender); modifications to a person's home or vehicle to accommodate the persons needs or the needs of their dependant, in the case of severe disability; palliative care for a terminal illness, for the person or a dependant; expenses associated with a dependant's death, funeral or burial.  In these cases, a release may only be approved where the person lacks the financial capacity to meet the relevant expense connected with the ground for release.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Support Registration
serviceDimensions.description: Child Support Registration: Child Support agreements are legally binding contracts that allow Child Support customers to mutually decide on the amount of child support payable. An agreement can include specific clauses, inflation factors and instructions to address periods of unemployment. Customers can apply for their agreement to be administered with, or in place of, a child support assessment.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Support Assessment
serviceDimensions.description: A customerï¿½s request to apply for a Child Support Assessment is the first interaction newly separated parents or non-parent carers have with Child Support. Child Supports objective is to encourage parental responsibility and self-reliance to establish appropriate and sustainable arrangements for the financial support of their child/ren.  An integral part of this process is to comprehend the customerï¿½s individual circumstances to provide information on available products and services and referrals that may assist parents to effectively manage their child support responsibilities.

serviceDimensions.name: Child Support Collection
serviceDimensions.description: Child Support Collection: A Child Support Payment is an amount of money transferred between separated parents used to help raise children whether they live in Australia or overseas. Child Support Payments can be transferred privately or the receiving parent can ask DHS to do it for them, once a Child Support Assessment has been done or have registered an agreement or court order with DHS.

serviceDimensions.name: ABSTUDY
serviceDimensions.description: Helps with costs for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Australians who are studying or undertaking an Australian Apprenticeship.

serviceDimensions.name: Family Tax Benefits
serviceDimensions.description: A 2 part payment that helps with the cost of raising children - Family Tax Benefit Part A and Part B.

serviceDimensions.name: Medical indemnity for insurers
serviceDimensions.description: To strengthen the availability of medical services in Australia, in 2002 the government introduced medical indemnity legislation. The legislation provides a package of financial assistance which helps keep medical indemnity insurance premiums at an affordable level. It does this by providing financial support to medical defence organisations (MDOs) and medical indemnity insurers (MIIs).

serviceDimensions.name: Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: Midwife Professional Indemnity Scheme provides financial assistance to eligible insurers who provide indemnity to eligible midwives.

serviceDimensions.name: Youth Allowance
serviceDimensions.description: Financial help for people aged 16 to 24 years who are studying full-time, undertaking a full-time Australian Apprenticeship, training, looking for work or sick.

serviceDimensions.name: Assistance for Isolated Children Scheme
serviceDimensions.description: Help for students who cannot go to an appropriate state school because of geographical isolation, disability or special health needs.
